{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_immokalee_ver01/data/sn95047334/00529042474/1958021301/0086.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES\nand continuing\nTHE CHATTAHOOCHEE TRIBUNE\nPublished each Thursday at 15 S. Madison Street\nA JOHN H. PERRi NEWSPAPER\nESTABLISHED 1901\nQuincy, Florida\nEntered in the post office at Quincy. Florida, und*r Ac* at\nMarch 5 1879 as matter of the second class.\nOne Year, $3.00 Two Years, $5.50 Six Months, $1.75\nJ. Ik Hutchinson Publisher\n_\nX NATIONAL EDITORIAL\n^o^2\nz bL4IR\u00abK\u00bb A\u00abl\u00bb4iiuiad\nThe (J. S. \"Sputnik\"\nThe successful launching of the U. S. earth satellite\nseems to have been a greater boost to the spirits of the\nfree world outside the United States than in it. This does\nnet mean Washington, the military services, Congress and\nthe average citizen was not pleased with the recent suc\ncessful army effort..\nHowever, most Americans felt that one of the services\nwould soon launch a successful satellite. People in Europe,\nnot as familiar with the diversity and lack of coordination\nbetween our three military services, were not so confident.\nMoreover, they are closer to Russia and to the Russian\nsuccess and their sense of relief was comparatively greater\nwhen the U. S. efforts succeeded.\nThe Navy's cause was done no good when an official\nhWy connected with Vanguard project announced, sev\nefd days after the successful Army effort, that he could fire\na rocket to the moon. It seems obvious now tiiat it is the\ndeed and not the word which counts, and this statement,\nblaming others for preventing the Navy from launching our\nrocket to the moon created a poor impression.\nFor the Army? which had almost been dealt out of the\nmissiles picture at one time, the go-ahead from high officials,\nand their successful launching, was a tremendous boost\nto morale. However, the Army's successful launching is a\nfarSesser achievement than either of Russia's first two suc\ncessful launchings.\nThe second successful Russian launching involved a\nsatellite weighing over 1,000 pounds. It is probably accurate\nto say the United States cannot today throw such a weighty\nobject into outer space, the Army satellite having weighed\nonly 30 pounds.\nBut the U. S. satellite is at least more specific, and more\nimpressive, than the metal \"peas\" which the Air Force fired\nfurther into outer space than any other object has ever been.\nAnd, U. S. propaganda, including publicity about our de\ncision to make available to the world all scientific data\nobtained from our satellite, was highly effective.\nNow that the first successful U. S. satellite is orbiting, we\nstill have a great distance to travel. We are still far behind\nthe Russians in this field and until we are capable of putting\nan orbit into outer space comparable to that which the\nRussians are reported to be readying (as this editorial is\nwritten) we will be an obvious second in this critical scien\ntifid race. Second is not good enough in these days and\ntimes.\nCause of the Recession\nVolumes are being written about the current recession\nin the United States. Predictions are being made by practic\nally every economist as to the length and depth, of the re\ncession. On one thing all agree: there is a recession, and\nit is a sharper one than the administration predicted.\nIn fact, President Eisenhower admitted only a few days\nago that the recession was more severe than the administra\ntion had anticipated. There is general agreement that the\nadministration, in its efforts to curb inflation, might have\nslowed down business growth. However, most of the econo\nmists who believe this also believe that the measures taken\nby the administration were necessary to curb inflation.\nIf this thesis is true, the question arises, \"what is the\nunderlying cause for the present recession?\nThe basic cause, in our opinion, is that the prosperity\nwa have been enjoying in the last few years (and bank de\nposits and total profits show that we have been enjoying\nprosperity) has been confined to too few people. This also\nhappened in the latter 1920'5, under some policies of the\ngovernment which have been paralleled, to a degree, in\nrecent years under the Eisenhower Administration.\nTake the farm program, for example. The soil bank pro\ngram allowed the farmer, and especially the big farmer, to\ndeposit money in the bank, but this money did not circulate\namong the fertilizer dealer, the laborer, the farm implement\ndealer, the seed dealer, and these dealers, in turn, did not\nspend their money with the newspaper, for advertising, etc.\nIn other words, the money did not circulate.\nBankers will admit today that their deposits are high,\nbut total deposits are in the hands of fewer people. Like\nwise, many big corporations have made fabulous profits\nin recent years, but many small businesses, and farmers,\nand white-collar workers caught in the cost spiral, have\nexperienced tight times. This is the reason for the depres\nsion, because it is the average person, the farmer, the white\ncedar worker, and the ordinary Joe, who buys most of the\ncars, refrigerators, stoves, etc. and who keeps the wheels\nof the economy turning.\nOne of Life's Mysteries\nOne of the mysteries of life, which we apparently can\u2019t\nis that of obtaining naturally-ripened fruit. The hard\ne\u00abb genuinely ripe variety to find is the banana, and it is\nunusual to find a really ripe banana in the stores, or on the\nfruitstands, today.\nWe have been told that this is because the shippers are\nnow ripening bananas with a chemical, and because they\nalso keep them too cold in transit so that they can store\nt^m longer. The net result is the shaft for the consumer\nseeking a good banana.\nprimes are becoming so desperate that it is even hard to\nf^d a good apple. And the citrus fruit, now that it is colored\nbeautifully (and artificially) is, most of the time, hardly\nworth eating. The morning grapefruit is just as likely to\ntaste like dry-cleaning fluid as it is a ripe grapefruit.\nGrowers have long since stopped growing the best canta\nloupes, at least in some parts of the country, in favor of\nbetter-shipping cantaloupes, and the same can be said for\nWatermelons. The net result of all this voo-doo is that the\ncounters of the stores are filled with beautiful fruit in bril-\nWt color, and much of it is not worth eating.\nAs far as we are concerned, we wish growers and\nsKppers had never been allowed to color their fruit, that\ndJ\u00dflhical ripening was prohibited by law, and that there\nwas a regulation requiring dealers to sell only ripened\nfruit But we admit, this is hoping for too much.\nTHE AMERICAN WAY\nmhurauy t? r let\nFXX) W 6 DC MONEY\nTO t t\nHOW TOUfee SONS\nX TO use IT/\nEEDEWL\nI WWxK\n/IMt\nAsking for Trouble\ngolden gloves\nI El o* AKImI\nI 0 KK9^^^HNU|\n_________\ngm i\nISi 1\nla S\nx s wwmbw J s\nJ UH\nKuf'\nARSON CLOSES SCHOOL \u2014Young vandals are blamed tor a\n$300,000 fire set in the school library of the Maplewood, N. J,\nJunior High School, leaving this mass of wreckage. The books\nhad been drenched with alcohol and set afire. The vandals\nstole food from the cafeteria and ransacked the principal\u2019s\noffice, stealing report cards that were ready to be mailed out.\nCROSSWOkD \u25a0mamgEm\nACROSS 0- Cased open- 19. Prose-\n1. Useless 9 mouthed cute\n5. Breaches 6. Emmets judici.\n9. Handle 7. Hawaiian ally\n(Rom. food 21. Chew\nAntiq.) 8. Scented- 22. Pink\n10. Wild ox filled bags ruby\n11. Likely 11. Astern spinel BnggflflHgfeoQ\n12. Science of (naut.) 23. Written\nlight to 12. Extraordi- defense iHAiPlSMPglwiejyi\u00df\nvision nary person 24. Bark\n14. Successes (slang) 25. Fire- Aeewet\n17. Exclama- 13. Painful arms 32. Place\ntion spots 27. Gasp 34. Capital of\n18. Disciplined 15. Island 29. Teutonic Yemen\n19. Indian (Malay characters 38. Bom\nweight Arch.) 30. Door joint 39. Thus\n20. Disfigure 16. Two-toed 31. A tear 40. Part of\n21. Unable to sloth jerker \u201cto be\u2019\u2019\nspeak\ni 1 1 1 r pt i r\n25. Conjecture 777 7\u201d T\u201d Vt7\\\n26. Armadillo W\n27.Playon 77)\nwords 6<z\n28. Cut off S is uT iT\"\n29. Ranches 0/\n(Sp.) 3\n33. Mulberry\n34. Happiness\n35. Voiced W/A//X//A I vA\n(Phonet.) ii is ZZ/fis I\n37. Egg of\na louse >o w I I\n38. Factor f/XrA\n39. Pudding ST 5\u00bb ><TKI\nstarch (EX) /Zt M I I _. I I\n41. Affirmative W\nvotes \u2014L.J.. _ \u2014J\n42. Foreboding 104^\n7,9 -r- Ly J\ndown\n1. Steam MM M M I KjM\n2. Cavities ZZ I\n3. Exist V/A VZ/L 111 KZZI\n4. Sodium\n(sym.)\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES, QUINCY, FLORIDA, THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 13, 1953\nWIN PENDLETON\nEverybody Hates Taxes Last\nweek, Hollywood celebrity Ron\nald Regan testified in favor of\nCongressman Syd Herlong\u2019s tax\nreduction bill before the House\nWays and Means Committee. Re\ngan claimed that because of the\nhigh income tax brackets that\nmost Hollywood stars lose their\nincentive to work. They see no\nneed to work when they can\u2019t\nkeep the money they earn, so\nthey make fewer pictures. This\nis hurting the business, Regan\nsaid, because it puts bit players\nand extras out of work. This ac\ncounts for the upsurge in foreign\nmoving picture production, he\nsaid. According to his testimony,\n15 percent of all pictures are\nnow being made overseas. Hol\nlywood\u2019s production is falling\noff. Herlong\u2019s bill would knock\ndown the top 90 percent income\nbracket to something like 42 per\ncent. (That\u2019s one worry we don\u2019t\nhave.)\nWomen\u2019s Luncheon High-\nomen\u2019s Luncheon High\nlight of the social schedule last\nweek was the annual Florida-\nGeorgia-South Carolina Dinner\nstaged by the Woman\u2019s National\nDemocratic Club; Senator Spes\nsard Holland, principal speaker;\nintroduced by South Carolina\u2019s\nCongressman W. J. Bryan Dorn.\nMrs. Aubrey Haley, wife of Con\ngressman Jim Haley, was pro\ngram chairman.\nThis affair worked out for Mrs.\nHaley better than two recent\nevents. They were the RCA ball\nand the Florida State Society re\nception. At the time, Mrs. Haley\nwas very happy, but later, when\nshe went to her clothes closet to\nwear \u201cthose same comfortable\nshoes\u2019* to the Holland dinner,\nshe discovered that for the pre\nvious functions she had worn one\nblue shoe and one black shoe.\n\u201cI still don\u2019t know whether any\none noticed it,\u201d she said. \u201cAt\nleast if they did, they were too\nIfouget\nthe best\nof brakes Buick's Award-Winning\nAir-Cooled Aluminum Brakes*\nconservatively, a IOOX im-\ntn the car of\nSPORTS CARS ILLUSTRATED. Feb.\nMagnificent Change\nCentury, SCI telle its readers:\n\u2022\u2022This was by far the most severe\ntest we ever have submitted a\nsedan\u2019s brakes to, but after it was\noverthe Buick's brakes functioned\nperfectly.\u201d\n\u20141\nnr* -\u00bbsJR\n...4. ggs \u00bbWW A\ni Z-CW lSK>g&\n1 h d z i'\ngyiry window \u00abl tvery B\u00bbkk l SAFETY PLATE Glen\nLook at everything you can have in the B-58 no wonder it\u2019s Buick\u2019s year to cheer\nB-58 DYNASTAR GRILLE stunning highlight of \"VELVET WALL\" SOUND SILENCIN G\u2014 scientifically\nthe new face of fashion. als out toad noises, heat and vibration.\nMIGHTY B-12000 ENGINE develops 12,000 SAFETY PLATE GLASS ALL AROUND protects\npounds of thrust behind each power stroke. you and your family-gives distortion-free visibility.\nSPECTACULAR PLIGHT PITCH DYNAFLOW*\u2014 SPARKLING NEW LUCITE PAINTS that retain\nswitches the pitch a million ways automatically their luster far longer\u2014optional at very little cost,\nprovides perfect power delivery. WORLD\u2019S FINEST POWER ACCESSORIES offer\nMIRACLE CHASSIS PLUS AIR RIDE* automati- y OU your choice of power options for steering, brak\ncally adjusts itself to every road and load, cradles fog, windows, seat adjustment, automatic head-lamp\nyour ride on 4 columns of air. dimmer\u2014even a power radio antenna.\nRUGGED X-BRACED CHASSIS WITH FAMOUS All engineered to the highest standards of\nBUICK ROTOFLO W TORQUE-TUBE DRlVE\u2014 gives quality and precision ever set by Buick\nyou the air ride at its buoyant best. F[ight pitch Dyna fl ow stan dard on umitbd and roadmastbi\nts.^-4 rri^^xT unan r a udc 75, optional at extra cost on other Series. Buick air ride optional\nDUAL VISTA-VISION HEAD LAMPS have 50 extra cost on all Series. Aluminum Front Brakes standard on all\nstronger \"brights\u201d\u20142s% stronger \"low\u201d beam. Series except. sveqal.\nEnjoy Swick\u2019s 2TV Show\u00bb-*'Th\u00ab Fofric* Munsol Show.\u201d jtorrinfl Fatric* Munsel, on ABC-TV ond _ _\n\u2019\u2019Tcloj ofWell* Fars\u00a9,\u201d \u00bbtarrinsDalaHobart\u00bbon, on NBC-TV *Wk ^^********^\u00bb__\nAAOk/~~ *ctfte f\nW\\ When better sotoinebilts art built\nv\\ Buick will build then\nI I I I I I I I \u00aby\u2014vi\nCUJ[J\nSEE YOUR AUTHORIZED BUICK DEALER\nt 4i\npolite to say anything to me\nabout it.\u201d\nRotary In Congress The\nfamous Rotary International \u201c4-\nway test\u201d of business ethics now\nrests on the desk of every Con\ngressman and Senator, thanks to\nJ. Arnold Carter, president of\nthe Delray Beach Rotary Club.\nCarter traveled to Washington\nlast week with 531 round glass\npaper weights which enclose the\nwords of the \u201ctest.\u201d With the\nhelp of his Congressman, Paul\nRogers, Carter distributed one\npaper weight to each member of\nthe House and Senate. The Ro\ntary words that each member\nwill have before him are:\n1. Is it the truth?\n2. Is it fair to all concerned?\n3. Will it build goodwill and\nbetter friendships?\n4. Will it be beneficial to all\nconcerned?\nListen For This One We\nlooked over the shoulder of Con\ngressman Billy Matthews the\nother day as he was working on\nan upcoming speech. Topic: the\nproblems of American education.\n\u201cThe present mood of the Con\ngress,\u201d he said, \u201cseems to be\nthat money can cure anything.\nIf we have a school problem,\nthen we can take care of it by\nappropriating a few million dol\nlars some people think. It\nisn\u2019t that simple. We must be\ngin with what and how we teach\nthe youngsters in the elementary\ngrades. That\u2019s part of what I\nplan to say.\u201d Mr. Billy ought\nto know what he\u2019s talking about.\nHe is a former school teacher.\nThanks For Lunch Monday\nwas free lunch day for the dozen\nnewsmen who cover Florida\nnews on Capitol Hill. Each year\nthe Florida Delegation throws a\nparty for us. Congressman Bob\nSikes, \u201cDean\u201d of the Delegation,\npresided. Charlie Bennett gave\na short welcoming address and\nSyd Herlong made a few clos\ning remarks. Speeches were\nshort. Thanks, now, until next\nyear.\nHE GETS THE FACTS FAST\nTucson, Ariz. Policeman\nFrank Greene quickly got the\nfacts when he went to investi-,\ngate a woman\u2019s complaint that\na small dog frequently nipped\nher leg. As he stepped from the\npatrol car, a small dog charged\nviciously and bit him on the\nleg.\nTHE QUIET MAN\nDallas, Texas \u2014A neurologist\n!says treatment for aphasia (loss i\nof speech) might be wasted on\nhenpecked husbands.\nDr. Joe R. Brown, of Roches\nter, Minn., told a clinical society\nabout trying to get a physical i\nhistory of a patient.\nThe man\u2019s wife answered\nevery question the doctor asked\nher husband. Seeking some dir\nect answers, Dr. Brown gently\nasked her to leave the room.\nFinding the husband couldn\u2019t I\nspeak, Dr. Brown called the wife\nback and apologized for not\nrealizing the man had aphasia I\nand couldn\u2019t speak a word. The\nwife was astonished she\ndidn't know it either!\nThere are any number of peo-\npie who are willing to borrow\nfive dollars. 3\n30th ANNIVERSARY'\n10 DAYS SPECIAL\n1000 LAMPS\n6 60 watt 120 volt clear or daylight\nRegular Price $2.10 Sale Price \u2014sl.oo\nWe are better qualified to do your\nElectrical Work. WHY?\n1. Always first in any NEW WIRING IMPROVEMENTS.\n2. Always first in SERVICE, all trucks are equipped with\n2 way Radio Communications, for FASTER service.\